          "title": "SOLID COLOR INTRO WITH IMAGE",
          "text": "“Everything was burning. Heat and black smoke hit my face. I looked up and saw a car hanging in a tree, also on fire.”<br><br>Maan breaks into fits of laughter at the ridiculousness of it all. This is what he remembers most vividly from the bomb attack in Aleppo, but he cannot explain why. Today, he is sitting in his living room on the small, stormy island of Bergsøy in Norway, far away from the fighting he escaped in the winter of 2015. The 38-year-old tells his story with disturbing ease, treating his pain like a work of fiction.<br><br>In January Sylvi Listhaug, the Norwegian Minister of Migration and Integration, gleefully announced on Facebook that the number of refugees in Norway was at its lowest in 20 years. Simultaneously, the number of displaced human beings worldwide hit a record high of 65.3 million. Has the Norwegian government lost sight of the global refugee crisis in an attempt to save its own skin?<br><br>Maan is just one voice that hints to the misery still trapped within Syria’s borders, and he fears the west has forgotten the humanitarian disaster that is still taking place.<br>",
          "buttons": "<a data-app-btn=\"true\" class=\"btn btn-primary\" href=\"https://mobirise.com\" data-toolbar=\"-mbrBtnMove\">MORE</a>"
