          "text": "<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 1.07rem; line-height: 1.5;\"><i>Syria, 22 December 2013</i></span></blockquote><p><br></p><p>It was a cold Sunday morning in Aleppo, Syria. The government offensive led by president Bashar Al-Assad, Operation Dawn of Victory, was coming to an end, leaving a ghost town of crumpled buildings and dust in its wake. Since the start of November, 1,200 people in Syria had been reported killed, at least 600 of whom were civilians. Some died from hunger, some from the cold, but most died in missile strikes conducted by the Assad Regime.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Maan Alrahim, a local taxi driver, was on his way to the local bakery to pick up 100 loaves of bread, a week’s supply of food for the families in his neighbourhood. Maan had volunteered for the task, not only because the war had left him without a job, but also because he feared a cluster of cars on the highway would appear as a slowly moving target to the bomber jets circling the city. If the traffic came to a standstill and he heard the propellers droning overhead, his friends would at least be safe in their homes.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>There were some other cars on the highway, but Maan could not hear any planes, and drove the two kilometres in silence. He did not listen to the radio, as he was afraid it would confirm more deaths, smoke rising from Aleppo's districts, disasters he already knew were happening. </p><p><span style=\"font-size: 1.07rem; line-height: 1.5;\"><br></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 1.07rem; line-height: 1.5;\">Upon his return he knew his neighbours would insist on paying him for the trouble, but he never accepted more than the price for the food, which usually amounted to 1,250 Syrian pounds, or £4.80. He would always leave before they offered him more.&nbsp;</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 1.07rem; line-height: 1.5;\">Food at the bakery was scarce, but they did have bread, and Maan returned to his car with a week’s supply. The drive had been worth the risk.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 1.07rem; line-height: 1.5;\"><br></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 1.07rem; line-height: 1.5;\">Yet, as he started approaching the middle of the highway, the cars in front of him were slowing. People started getting out, and the thud of giant wings echoed with the rumble of stationary vehicles. Maan knew what would happen next.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Pulse roaring in his ears, he slammed his car door shut and started running for the nearest building in sight, a small kiosk 50 metres away.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Behind him on the road, the first bomb hit, causing the ground to tremble as if a earthquake had hit it. Smoke made his eyes sting. People were screaming.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Maan made the terrible mistake of looking up, and saw the next shell before it struck the ground, a giant metal object set for destruction. His feet hit the concrete once, twice, and although he never heard the explosion, he suddenly found himself on his back, without the ability to hear or see.&nbsp;</p>"
        },
