        {
          "_tags": [
            "Theme"
          ],
          "_name": "content1",
          "_anchor": "content1-a",
          "_params": {
            "paddingTop": 1,
            "paddingBottom": 1,
            "bgColor": "#fff"
          },
          "text": "<p>He would later learn that Assad’s helicopters had dropped three bombs on the highway. The first was to prevent the cars from escaping, the second was sent to kill, and the third Maan never saw. For the first two to five minutes, he was engulfed by a shroud of black smoke. When it started clearing, he found himself inside the kiosk, trapped by fallen shelves.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I could not feel anything below my hips, but was sure I had made it out okay,” Maan says. “When I tried to get up, I discovered my body was stuck in a seated position. The first thing I thought was:  ‘Why am I sitting?’ I did not understand.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Then I looked down, and saw my shin facing the ceiling. Both of my legs were shattered, and I was sitting in a pool of my own blood.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Suddenly, the air inside the kiosk felt swelteringly hot. Maan grabbed the nearest shelves and started pulling, desperate to reach the people on the road outside. After several minutes he was able to clear a path to the door, and dragged his body across the doorstep and onto the pavement. The first thing he saw was a car hanging in a tree with fire pouring out its windows, licking black streaks in its once-white paintwork.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The people around him sounded like they were yelling in a different language, but Maan did the same, screaming for help at the top of his lungs. At last, he heard a man’s voice through the wreckages. The stranger approached him and asked if he could walk. Maan said no, so a group of volunteers carried him to a nearby van. There were no ambulances in sight.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“He threw me in the boot,” he says. “That was a great thing, no problem! At least I was on my way to a hospital.”</p><p><br></p><p>The volunteers picked up all the injured people they could find, pushing them into the van as quickly as possible, as they feared the helicopters would return if they discovered there were any survivors.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>As they approached the Red Crescent hospital, the Arab equivalent to the Red Cross, the van was blocked more than 50 people, whose injuries made Maan's stomach flip, and he had to look away. Outside the next hospital were another 20, but the third hospital welcomed the group of survivors.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“The first thing the doctor said was that he couldn’t do anything. I had lost a lot of blood, my tendons and muscles were ruined, and the bones were broken in several places,” he said. “Through all of this I could not close my eyes.” Maan feared that if he fell asleep, he would never wake up again.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>He was sent to a fourth hospital, which was half an hour drive away by ambulance. This was located close to his brother’s home, and he ran into an acquaintance while waiting on the floor of the hospital hallway, his clothes so drenched in blood that at first he was not recognised. He asked the man to find his brother, to tell him that he was injured, but not to notify his wife, Fatima. Maan didn’t want her to fear for his life. The man said he would, and left the hospital immediately.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>After watching his friend burst out the doors, Maan focused all his energy on the voices, terrified of falling asleep. He was sure that if he did, the doctors would stop trying to help, thinking that he was dead. The medical personnel were speaking in hushed voices, but Maan could hear every word they spoke.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The man in charge was speaking to the Red Crescent, the first hospital they had approached. He said that Maan was in desperate need of blood and artificial tendons, and that without Red Moon’s help they would have to amputate. Maan did not feel anything at the time, too numbed by pain and exhaustion, but is now beyond relieved that the hospital said yes. &nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The bomb had hit at 10 in the morning, and at five past two in the afternoon, after an ambulance ride he could barely remember, Maan was in the operating theatre.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“That was it,” he said. “I could finally sleep.”</p>"
        },
