        {
          "_tags": [
            "Theme"
          ],
          "_name": "content1",
          "_anchor": "content1-c",
          "_params": {
            "paddingTop": 1,
            "paddingBottom": 1,
            "bgColor": "#fff"
          },
          "text": "<p>Nearly two years later, after months trying to cross the border into Turkey (he was finally smuggled into the country across a dried-out riverbed), surviving severe infections and more than fifteen operations, and spending a year in hospital not knowing whether he would ever see his family again, the UN helped Maan, his wife Fatima and their three children get to Norway.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Their nightmare was over, but Maan considers himself more than lucky. Under the current government led by the Progress Party, the number of people staying at Norwegian refugee centres has halved over the course of 2016, and is expected to decrease even more. The Minister of Migration and Integration, Sylvi Listhaug, is thrilled: </p><p><br></p><p>\n\n“I am very happy with the fact that the number of arrivals at our reception centres for refugees in 2016 was the lowest in almost 20 years,” she posted on Facebook on January 5th.\n<span style=\"font-size: 1.07rem; line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 1.07rem; line-height: 1.5;\"><br></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 1.07rem; line-height: 1.5;\">Is this abrupt tightening of immigration policies a result of xenophobia, or has Norway advanced from feeling helpless to a state of willfull ignorance? Maan believes the general public is simply uninformed.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“They speak very little of [Aleppo] in newspapers and on TV. Here in Norway it is legal to work for the newspapers, in Syria it is not. You can’t take pictures, and you can’t speak to people on the outside.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“Two or three months ago, my uncle and his family were asleep in their house at five in the morning. A plane came in and bombed their house, and his whole family died in their beds. Him, his wife and their two children. One was very small. Nobody mentioned that in the papers.”</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Finished telling his story, Maan looks at me with kind, confident eyes, pressing that Norway has really treated him very well. His home on Bergsøy is humble but roomy, and he shares it with his mother, his wife Fatima and their three children.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Today he has just come back from driving on an ice rink, which one of the final stages to getting a driver’s licence in Norway, and is determined to pass his test.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>“I don’t know many people have made it to Norway,” he says, as a way of closing the conversation. And there it is. Maan has access to free healthcare, his children all have places at the local school and nursery, and the government is paying their rent.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The refugees that do get residence permits, although very far from home, have the same rights as the average Norwegian, but these only constitute 30% of those who apply. The important question is: what happens to the other 70%?&nbsp;</p>"
        },
